  "enhanced_information": "In the palliation of dyspnoea in cancer lung patients, the use of a morphine patch is supported by consensus as it binds to opioid receptors, effectively reducing the perception of breathlessness and providing significant relief (95% confidence). Diazepam and clobazam, while having sedative effects that may reduce anxiety and potentially improve dyspnoea perception, are less effective and not primarily indicated for dyspnoea management (60% and 55% confidence, respectively). Haloperidol, an antipsychotic, may also provide sedation and reduce anxiety, but its role in dyspnoea palliation is limited and less effective (50% confidence). Therefore, the morphine patch is the most appropriate option for managing dyspnoea in this context."
